Neural networks are universal

Every continuous \(f\colon [0,1]^n \to \mathbb{R}^m\) can be approximated by a neural network with

  • one layer with an exponential number of perceptrons
  • standard activation functions and
  • suitable weights that need to be learned

How does a Neural Network learn?

Learning in epochs

Common loss functions for regression

Task: Rate the prediction \(\tilde{y} \in \mathbb{R}^n\) of the true value \(y \in \mathbb{R}^n\)

mean squared error

\(\frac{1}{n}\sqrt{\sum_i (\tilde{y}_i - y_i)^2}\)

steep for large errors

mean absolute error

\(\frac{1}{n}{\sum_i |\tilde{y}_i - y_i|}\)

steep for small errors

log cosh

\(\frac{1}{n}{\sum_i \log\cosh(\tilde{y}_i - y_i)}\)

just right

Common loss functions for classification

binary classification

  • true value \(y\) is either \(0\) or \(1\)
  • prediction \(\tilde{y}\) is a probability

binary crossentropy

\(n\)-class classification

  • \(y = (0,\ldots,0,1,0,\ldots,0)\) indicates the true class
  • \(\tilde{y}=(\tilde{y}_{1},\ldots,\tilde{y}_{n})\)
    is a probability distribution

categorical crossentropy

\(-\sum_i y_i \log \tilde{y}_i\)

Gradient descent

  • compute gradient of loss \(L\) w.r.t. weights \(w\)

    \[ \displaystyle \frac{\partial {L}}{\partial w} = \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial\tilde{y}}\frac{ \partial \tilde{y}}{\partial{w}} \]

  • find the direction \(\Delta w\) of steepest descent

  • take small step into this direction
    (with random step size or advanced optimizer)

Computations expressed by graphs

forward pass \(\leadsto\) results

backward pass \(\leadsto\) gradients

Low-level framework: TensorFlow

https://playground.tensorflow.org

Gradient descent in formulas

Start with random \(w^{(0)}\) and compute \(w^{(1)}, w^{(2)}, \ldots\) according to

\[ w^{(t+1)} = w^{(t)} - \eta^{(t)} \cdot \sum_{x,y} \frac{\partial L(y,\tilde{y}(x,w^{(t)}))}{\partial w^{(t)}} \]

  • \(\eta^{(t)}\) … learning rate, usually chosen to decay

  • summation over

    • one random training sample (\(\Rightarrow\) stochastic gradient descent) or
    • all training samples (\(\Rightarrow\) batch gradient descent) or
    • batches of training samples (\(\Rightarrow\) mini-batch gradient descent)

Optimize the optimizer!

Momentum

\[ \begin{cases} \displaystyle v^{(t+1)} \!\!\!\! &= \gamma \cdot v^{(t)} + \eta^{(t)} \cdot \sum_{x,y} \frac{\partial L(y,\tilde{y}(x,w^{(t)}))}{\partial w^{(t)}} \\ \displaystyle w^{(t+1)} \!\!\!\! &= w^{(t)} - v^{(t+1)} \qquad (\gamma \approx 0.9) \end{cases} \]

move like a ball rolling downhill

Nesterov accelerated gradients

let the ball look ahead

Adagrad

  • high \(\eta\) for rarely changed weights
  • low \(\eta\) for often changed weights

Adadelta

same but look at recent changes

Adam

think Adadelta with momentum

\(\Rightarrow\) S. Ruder. An overview of gradient descent optimization algorithms. arXiv:1609.04747

The SoftMax activation function

vector

\((z_1,\ldots,z_n)\)

 

\(\mapsto\)

probabilities

\((y_1,\ldots,y_n)\)

where

\(y_i = \frac{e^{z_i}}{\sum_j e^{z_j}}\)

How-To: Sequential models with Keras

Build…

from keras import layers, models

model = models.Sequential([
            layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'),
        ], input_shape=(max_len,))
model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

Compile…

model.compile(optimizer="Adam",
              loss="categorical_crossentropy")

Train…

history = model.fit(X, y, epochs=10, 
                    batch_size=32, validation_split=0.2)

Apply…

y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

Our approaches

character-level and word-level convolutional nets

1D-Convolutional layers

What
sliding-window perceptron
Why
extract patterns
Keras Layer
Conv1D(filters, kernel_size)
  • filters: output dimension (here 3)
  • kernel_size: window size (here 2)

2D-Convolutional layers

Keras layer
Conv2D(filters, kernel_size, strides, padding)

Global Pooling layers

What
component-wise aggregation
Why
get global features
When
after convolutional layers
Keras
GlobalMaxPooling1D(), …

Pooling layers

What
sliding-window aggregation
Why
get macroscopic features
When
after convolutional layers
Keras
MaxPooling1D(), AveragePooling1D(), …

Embedding layer

What
map indices to vectors with a look-up table
Why
one-hot encoding is large
When
immediately after input
Keras
Embedding(input_dim, output_dim)

Preprocessing steps

Word embeddings

What
map words to vectors (typical dim 96-300)
Idea
train encoder-decoder-net to fill gaps in phrases
Algorithms

How-To: Functional models with Keras

Use Input to define an input tensor,

inputs = layers.Input(shape=(max_len,))

apply Layer instance to tensor(s) to get an output tensor,

conv1 = layers.Conv1D(128, kernel_size=3, activation='relu') 
res1 = GlobalMaxPooling()(conv1(inputs))
conv2 = layers.Conv1D(128, kernel_size=7, activation='relu') 
res2 = GlobalMaxPooling()(conv2(inputs))
outputs = Dense(3, activation='softmax')(Concatenate([res1, res2]))

and construct a Model declaring input and output tensors

model = models.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)

Dropout Layer

What
randomly drop input components
Why
regularization
When
after dense layers
Keras Layer
Dropout(rate=0.5)

Batch Normalization Layer

 

\(\to\)

 

What
for each batch, rescale input components (mean 0, variance 1)
Why
regularization

 

When
after convolutional layers and before activation
Keras Layer
BatchNormalization()

Statistics for bags of words

  • Occurence: does word \(w\) occur in document \(D\)?
  • Count \(\ \#(w,D)\): how often does \(w\) occur in document \(D\)?
  • Term Frequency: \(\ \displaystyle \mathsf{tf}(w,D) = \frac{\#(w,D)}{\max_v \#(v,D)}\)

When is word \(w\) characteristic for document \(D\)?

  • high Inverse Document Frequency: \(\ \displaystyle \mathsf{idf}(w) = \log \frac{N}{N_w}\)
    (\(N\) … number of documents, \(N_w\) … number of documents with \(w\))

\(\leadsto\) high TF-IDF-measure: \(\ \displaystyle \mathsf{tf}(w,D) \cdot \mathsf{idf}(w)\)

Recurrent layers

What
sliding stateful meta-perceptron
Why / Why not
natural for sequence processing
but expensive and difficult to train
Keras Layers
LSTM(units), GRU(units), CudnnLSTM(units), CudnnGRU(units)
